alternatives.transcript: Hi there. This is Chris, and I'm going to show you how to use the l s command when you're logged into the Linux Smith computers. And to do that, it's pretty simple. You actually, once you're logged in, there's a command called l s, just l s and it will list all the files in your folder. I happen to have a whole bunch of files in my home folder here. But if we, let's say we're gonna go into my one zero seven folder with the c d command, which is covered in a different video. I can type l s and get all the files in there and that's the basic way of using the command, but the ls command has lots of different flags that go along with it. So you can type ls dash l and it will list all your files, all the non hidden files as it turns out in a, an interesting format here that, tells you more information about the files. It tells you in fact how big the file is and it tells you whether the file is a directory or not. The little d at the beginning here means that it's a directory. So the assign zero folder in the old and the pandoc folder here are, all, directories. So if I type c d to change directory into the pandoc folder, it will, go into there and then that's that's an actual folder that I can do l s on and see all the files in that folder as well. Some of the other, flags that you can use, I like the l s dash one which lists them all out one after the other and then I can just scroll back and back and up and down here and see them like that. Sometimes that's nice. As I said, the l s dash l works great. L s dash al means even show me the hidden files as well. So in this case, there's a couple of files that are hidden. Files that begin with a period are all hidden on your in your folder system. So anything that's actually starts with a period is hidden, including the two interesting directories called dot, which means the current directory that you're in, and dot dot, which means your previous directory. And that's also covered in a different video on the c d command and working directories and so forth. If you wanna know more information about LS and all the different flags, you can type man LS for the manual page and it gives you the manual page here and it says all the different types of flags and there's a ton of flags for for the ls command. And by the way, I'm just using the arrow keys to to go down in this file and see all the different commands. You can also type q to quit out of the manual page. My favorite l s command is l s dash a l r t, which means list all the files including the hidden ones, list them in that special format that gives me more information, list them in reverse order, and list them by time. So what this actually does is it lists the files in the reverse order from when they were created. This directory is not the best one to do it. Let's go into a previous directory. L s dash a l r t says, okay. I created the old folder, the most, most passed and the newest folder happens to be the pan doc folder here, which is, like that. So I like the l s dash a l r t to give you just a listing of, like, hey, which files did I modify most recently? Those are ones at the bottom of the folder. So that's it for the l s command. You will use this every single time you log on to the myth computers, and you should get used to it. Thanks.
